===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{Han compound|又|肉|t2=meat|ls=psc|c1=p|c2=s}}. The hand shape has been abstracted to {{och-l|*𠂇}}; compare {{och-l|*右}}, where {{och-l|*又}} has also taken this shape. The {{och-l|*肉}} in turn has taken the form of {{och-l|*⺼}}.

The character may have been the original form of {{och-l|侑|to urge to eat}}. Alternatively, it may be the original form of  {{och-l|醢|gloss=minced pickled meat}}, which also has the {{och-l|又}} element as phonetic.

Folk etymology traditionally explains it as a hand holding meat, hence “in possession of”. However, the oracle bone script shows no meat.

''{{w|Shuowen Jiezi}}'' and other ancient sources have erroneously analyzed the character as a {{Han compound|又|c1=p|月|c2=s|t2=moon|ls=psc|nocap=1}}. ''Shuowen Jiezi'' defines {{lang|zh|有}} as "{{lang|zh|不宜有也}}" ("[to have something that] not should be had"), citing the ''{{w|Spring and Autumn Annals}}'' ({{lang|zh|春秋傳}}): "{{lang|zh|日月有食之}}" ("There are solar and lunar eclipses"). As eclipses were not auspicious to the Chinese, they were "something that should not be happening". The {{lang|zh|月}} component alludes to the inauspicious lunar eclipse.

===Etymology===
Possibly Sino-Tibetan. Compare {{cog|bo|ཡོད||to be; to have}}. Related to:

* {{och-l|侑|gloss=to offer, to sacrifice}} [causative, i.e. “to cause to have”]
* {{och-l|又|gloss=again}} [adverbial]
* {{och-l|或|gloss=some; or}} [indefinite]

